MODULE 3: VEHICLE ASSIGNMENT (GREEDY ALGORITHMS)
🎯 Objective

Efficiently assign delivery requests to vehicles such that:

Maximum number of deliveries are completed
Vehicle capacity is not exceeded
High-value deliveries are prioritized
Decisions are made quickly (real-time)
🚚 Real-World Interpretation

You have:

Multiple vehicles (limited capacity)
Multiple packages (different weights, deadlines, priorities)

👉 Problem:

“Which packages should go in which vehicle?”

⚙️ DESIGN STRATEGY

We use Greedy Algorithms because:

Fast decisions required
Works well in real-time logistics
Gives near-optimal solutions
🔸 1. Activity Selection (Max Deliveries)
✅ Idea:

Select maximum deliveries without deadline conflict

🔧 Approach:
Sort deliveries by earliest deadline
Pick delivery if it fits schedule
Code:
bool compareDeadline(Delivery a, Delivery b) {
    return a.deadline < b.deadline;
}

void activitySelection(vector<Delivery>& arr) {
    sort(arr.begin(), arr.end(), compareDeadline);

    int last = -1;

    cout << "Selected Deliveries:\n";

    for (auto d : arr) {
        if (d.deadline > last) {
            cout << d.id << " ";
            last = d.deadline;
        }
    }
}
🧠 Viva Line:

“Activity selection maximizes the number of deliveries completed within deadlines.”

🔸 2. Fractional Knapsack (Max Value per Trip)
✅ Idea:

Maximize total delivery value within vehicle capacity

👉 You can take partial deliveries (theoretical case)

🔧 Code:
struct Item {
    int value, weight;
};

bool compareRatio(Item a, Item b) {
    return (double)a.value/a.weight > (double)b.value/b.weight;
}

double fractionalKnapsack(int W, vector<Item>& items) {
    sort(items.begin(), items.end(), compareRatio);

    double totalValue = 0.0;

    for (auto item : items) {
        if (W >= item.weight) {
            totalValue += item.value;
            W -= item.weight;
        } else {
            totalValue += item.value * ((double)W / item.weight);
            break;
        }
    }

    return totalValue;
}
🧠 Viva Line:

“Fractional knapsack maximizes profit per vehicle by selecting highest value-to-weight deliveries first.”

🔸 3. Job Scheduling with Deadlines
✅ Idea:

Maximize profit while meeting deadlines

🔧 Code:
struct Job {
    int id, deadline, profit;
};

bool compareProfit(Job a, Job b) {
    return a.profit > b.profit;
}

void jobScheduling(vector<Job>& jobs) {
    sort(jobs.begin(), jobs.end(), compareProfit);

    int n = jobs.size();
    vector<int> slot(n, -1);

    int totalProfit = 0;

    for (auto job : jobs) {
        for (int j = job.deadline - 1; j >= 0; j--) {
            if (slot[j] == -1) {
                slot[j] = job.id;
                totalProfit += job.profit;
                break;
            }
        }
    }

    cout << "Total Profit: " << totalProfit << endl;
}
🧠 Viva Line:

“Job scheduling ensures high-profit deliveries are completed before their deadlines.”
